# React Native Component Patterns

## Screen Components Are Thin Orchestrators

Screens live in `src/screens/`. Their only jobs are: read from Zustand stores, derive minimal local state, and pass data down to presentational children. Significant JSX logic, large inline style blocks, and UI sub-components should not live inline inside a screen.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD — screen doing too much inline
export default function HomeScreen() {
  const users = useFirebaseStore((s) => s.users);
  return (
    <View>
      <View style={{ flexDirection: "row", padding: 12, ... }}>
        <TextInput onChangeText={...} />
      </View>
      <FlatList data={users} renderItem={({ item }) => (
        <View style={{ ... }}>
          <Text>{item.displayName}</Text>
          <Text>{item.username}</Text>
        </View>
      )} />
    </View>
  );
}

// ✅ GOOD — screen delegates to focused children
export default function HomeScreen() {
  const users = useFirebaseStore((s) => s.users);
  const [filter, setFilter] = useState("");
  return <UserList users={users} filter={filter} onFilterChange={setFilter} />;
}
```

## Sub-Components Do One Thing

UI components live in `src/components/`. Each component should have a single, named responsibility. Prefer many small focused components over one large one.

```javascript
// ❌ BAD — catch-all component
function ConversationCard({ conversation, user, onPress, onDelete, showBadge }) { ... }

// ✅ GOOD — focused components composed together
function ConversationRow({ conversation }) { ... }
function UnreadBadge({ count }) { ... }
function ConversationActions({ onDelete }) { ... }
```

## Co-location Rule

If a sub-component is only used by one screen, it may live alongside that screen file in `src/screens/`. If it's used in two or more places, move it to `src/components/`.

## State Management — 3-Store Zustand Architecture

This project uses three Zustand stores with strict separation of concerns. Never blur these boundaries.

| Store | File | What goes here |
|---|---|---|
| `useFirebaseStore` | `stores/firebaseStore.js` | All Firestore data: users, conversations, messages, currentUser. Updated only by Firestore `onSnapshot` listeners or store-owned subscriptions. |
| `useLocalStore` | `stores/localStore.js` | UI-only state: drafts, `isSending`, `isLoadingConversation`. Never persisted to Firebase. |
| `usePresenceStore` | `stores/presenceStore.js` | Realtime Database presence data: `isOnline`, `lastSeen`. Updated only by `onValue` listeners. |

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD — reading from the right store for the right concern
const messages = useFirebaseStore((s) => s.messages[conversationId] || []);
const inputText = useLocalStore((s) => s.drafts[conversationId] || "");
const isOnline = usePresenceStore((s) => s.presenceData[userId]?.isOnline);
```

## Store-Owned Subscriptions

Firestore `onSnapshot` listeners that feed global state belong in the store (or in a util called once from `AppNavigator`), not in individual screens. Screens should read from the store; they should not start their own listeners for globally shared data (users, conversations).

```javascript
// ❌ BAD — screen starts its own listener for shared data
useEffect(() => {
  const unsub = onSnapshot(collection(db, "users"), (snap) => {
    setUsers(snap.docs.map((d) => ({ userId: d.id, ...d.data() })));
  });
  return unsub;
}, []);

// ✅ GOOD — store owns the subscription; screen just reads
// AppNavigator calls: useFirebaseStore.getState().subscribeToUsers()
const users = useFirebaseStore((s) => s.users);
```

## Fetch Effects — Always Add Ignore + Cleanup

Any one-off async fetch inside a `useEffect` must use an ignore boolean to guard state updates after unmount, and return a cleanup function.

```javascript
// ✅ GOOD
useEffect(() => {
  let ignore = false;

  const loadData = async () => {
    try {
      setLoading(true);
      const result = await fetchSomething(id);
      if (!ignore) setData(result);
    } catch (err) {
      if (!ignore) console.error(err);
    } finally {
      if (!ignore) setLoading(false);
    }
  };
  loadData();

  return () => { ignore = true; };
}, [id]);
```

For screens with both an initial load and a user-triggered refresh, define the async function outside the effect (accepting a `getIgnore` param) and use a dedicated `handleRefresh` handler — don't call the same effect for refreshes.

## Communicating with the Backend Agent

The agent endpoint lives at `POST /api/agent`. Send requests from `src/services/aiService.js` using `fetch` with `Authorization: Bearer <idToken>`. Never call the backend directly from a screen; go through the service layer.

```javascript
// src/services/aiService.js
export const executeAgent = async (userQuery, conversationId, onChunk) => {
  const idToken = await getIdToken();
  const response = await fetch(`${BACKEND_URL}/api/agent`, {
    method: "POST",
    headers: {
      "Content-Type": "application/json",
      Authorization: `Bearer ${idToken}`,
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({ userQuery, conversationId }),
  });
  // stream chunks via onChunk callback
};
```

## Helper Functions — WET Until Three Instances

One duplication is intentional and acceptable. The rule triggers at **three instances** — when the same helper appears in a third file, extract it to `src/utils/` and import it everywhere.

```javascript
// ✅ fine — used in two screens, leave it
// HomeScreen.js has getInitials(), ChatScreen.js has getInitials() — ok

// ❌ triggers extraction — same helper in 3+ files
// src/utils/helpers.js
export function getInitials(name) { ... }
export function getAvatarColor(id) { ... }
```
